[2] China: China National Health Commission 9 Mar 2020
Date: Tue 10 Mar 2020
Source: China National Health Commission [in Chinese, machine trans., edited]
http://www.nhc.gov.cn/xcs/yqtb/202003/b4abcf83e53d4284b2981c75917385eb.shtml


At 04:00 on [10 Mar 2020], 31 provinces (autonomous regions, municipalities) and the Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps reported 24 new confirmed cases, 22 new deaths (22 in Hubei), and 31 new suspected cases.

On the same day, 1578 cases were cured and discharged, 3235 persons were removed from close contact with medical observation, and 302 severe cases were reduced.

As of 24:00 on [10 Mar 2020], according to reports from 31 provinces (autonomous regions, municipalities) and the Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps, there were 16 145 confirmed cases (including 4492 severe cases), 61 475 cured cases, and 3158 who died. A total of 80 778 confirmed cases have been reported, and there are currently 285 suspected cases. A total of 675 886 close contacts have been tracked, and 14 607 close contacts are still in medical observation.

There were 13 new confirmed cases in Hubei (13 in Wuhan), 1471 new cases cured (1212 in Wuhan), 22 new deaths (19 in Wuhan), and 15 671 confirmed cases (14 514 in Wuhan). Among them, 4412 were severe cases (4217 in Wuhan). A total of 49 056 discharged patients were cured (33 041 in Wuhan), a total of 3046 deaths (2423 in Wuhan), and a total of 67 773 confirmed cases (49 978 in Wuhan). There were 6 new suspected cases (6 in Wuhan) and 198 suspected cases (192 in Wuhan).

At 04:00 on [10 Mar 2020], 10 newly diagnosed imported cases were reported (6 in Beijing, 2 in Shanghai, 1 in Shandong, and 1 in Gansu). As of 24:00 on [10 Mar 2020], a total of 79 imported confirmed cases were reported overseas.

A total of 177 confirmed cases were reported from Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan: 120 cases in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (65 cases discharged, 3 deaths), 10 cases in the Macau Special Administrative Region (10 cases discharged), and 47 cases in Taiwan (17 cases discharged, 1 death).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the report above, a total of 80 778 cases of confirmed COVID-19 have now been reported from China, representing an increase of 24 cases in the past 24 hours, of which 13 (54.2%) were in Hubei province. It is the 4rd consecutive day that the number of newly reported cases in a 24 hour period was less than 50. As I mentioned in yesterday's post (20200310.7070560), daily case counts less than 20 were last reported in mid-January 2020 when the conclusion was there still had not been person-to-person transmission identified (see Novel coronavirus (04): China (HU), Thailand ex China, WHO 20200114.6889527, section [3] for discussion). While there are still suspected cases reported that presumably are waiting for laboratory confirmation, fingers are crossed this adequately represents China approaching interruption of transmission of the SARS-CoV-2. In addition, 22 deaths were reported, all of them by Hubei province. Five new cases were reported from Hong Kong.

Of note is the increasing numbers of imported cases mentioned with 10 newly imported cases (6 in Beijing, 2 in Shanghai, 1 in Shandong, and 1 in Gansu), bringing the total number of imported cases to 79. If the imported cases are counted in the daily totals, then 41.7% of the newly confirmed cases mentioned in today's (10 Mar 2020) update were imported cases. A challenge will be to prevent importations from starting new chains of transmission.

A map of China showing provinces can be seen at https://www.chinadiscovery.com/china-maps/china-provincial-map.html, and a HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7075036,155. - Mod.MPP]

