Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[This observation was also given by Dr Bruce Aylward, head of the WHO mission that went to China, in an interview upon his return, although I have been unable to locate the interview to link it here. It has been demonstrated that the ACE-2 receptor site is cell entry site for the SARS-CoV-2, The observation that more serious outcomes including death were observed in individuals with hypertension makes one wonder if data are being collected looking at those with hypertension treated with ACE inhibitors versus those using other types of antihypertensive medications.

Kuba K, Imai Y, and Penninger JM postulate that stimulating ACE2 activity might be a means of mitigating acute lung injury, including those seen with ARDS (Acute respiratory distress syndrome) such as seen with SARS-CoV and SARS-CoV-2 infection. In contrast, I wonder if suppression of the ACE2 activity to maintain good blood pressure control may well predispose individuals to more severe acute lung injury due to the absence of ACE2 activity.

Kuba, Imai, and Penninger postulate that enhancing ACE2 activity (as opposed to inhibiting it through ACE inhibitors used for hypertension control,) may well be a strategy for reducing lung damage during events associated with acute lung injury.

ref: Kuba K, Imai Y, Penninger JM. Angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 in lung diseases. Curr Opin Pharmacol. 2006; 6(3): 271-6; https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1471489206000579?via%3Dihub
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
The renin-angiotensin system (RAS) plays a key role in maintaining blood pressure homeostasis, as well as fluid and salt balance. Angiotensin II, a key effector peptide of the system, causes vasoconstriction and exerts multiple biological functions. Angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) plays a central role in generating angiotensin II from angiotensin I, and capillary blood vessels in the lung are one of the major sites of ACE expression and angiotensin II production in the human body. The RAS has been implicated in the pathogenesis of pulmonary hypertension and pulmonary fibrosis, both commonly seen in chronic lung diseases such as chronic obstructive lung disease. Recent studies indicate that the RAS also plays a critical role in acute lung diseases, especially acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS). ACE2, a close homologue of ACE, functions as a negative regulator of the angiotensin system and was identified as a key receptor for SARS (severe acute respiratory syndrome) coronavirus infections. In the lung, ACE2 protects against acute lung injury in several animal models of ARDS. Thus, the RAS appears to play a critical role in the pathogenesis of acute lung injury. Indeed, increasing ACE2 activity might be a novel approach for the treatment of acute lung failure in several diseases.

References
----------
1. Imai Y, Kuba K, Rao S, et al. Angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 protects from severe acute lung failure. Nature. 2005; 436(7047): 112-116. doi:10.1038/nature03712; https://www.nature.com/articles/nature03712
2. Zhang M, Gao Y, Zhao W, Yu G, Jin F. ACE-2/ANG1-7 ameliorates ER stress-induced apoptosis in seawater aspiration-induced acute lung injury. Am J Physiol Lung Cell Mol Physiol. 2018; 315(6): L1015-L1027. doi:10.1152/ajplung.00163.2018; https://journals.physiology.org/doi/full/10.1152/ajplung.00163.2018.
3. Li Y, Zeng Z, Li Y, et al. Angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibition attenuates lipopolysaccharide-induced lung injury by regulating the balance between angiotensin-converting enzyme and angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 and inhibiting mitogen-activated protein kinase activation. Shock. 2015; 43(4): 395-404. doi:10.1097/SHK.0000000000000302; https://journals.lww.com/shockjournal/fulltext/2015/04000/Angiotensin_Converting_Enzyme_Inhibition.13.aspx.
- Mod.MPP]

